"""
mkt-christ — Numbers chapters 22–24 (Balaam cycle)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-numbers-22-24.py

96 verses: ch22 (41), ch23 (30), ch24 (25).
Key Christological connections:
- Angel of YHWH in ch22 as Christophany (pre-incarnate appearance); donkey/opened eye
- Balaam as prophetic type: constrained to speak only YHWH's word → John 12:49
- Ch23 v.19: God not a man who lies → Heb 6:18 (incarnation paradox)
- Ch23 v.21: YHWH with them → Immanuel (Matt 1:23; John 1:14)
- Ch23 v.22 / Ch24 v.8: 'out of Egypt' → Matt 2:15 (Hos 11:1)
- Ch24 v.17: Star of Jacob → Rev 22:16 (bright morning star); Matt 2:2 (Magi)
- Ch24 v.9: Lion of Judah at rest → Rev 5:5
- Curse/blessing reversal → Gal 3:13; Rom 8:31-39
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Israel camped in the plains of Moab beyond the Jordan at Jericho. The plains of Moab are the threshold of the promised land — the last encampment before the conquest begins. The entire Balaam narrative occurs on this threshold, while Israel waits. Christ's ministry similarly occurred at the threshold of the kingdom's arrival: 'The time is fulfilled, and the kingdom of God is at hand; repent and believe in the gospel' (Mark 1:15). The threshold-moment is where the powers arrayed against the covenant people make their final attempt to use spiritual means to destroy what YHWH has promised.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Balak son of Zippor saw all that Israel had done to the Amorites. The report of YHWH's victories on behalf of Israel reaches the nations and generates fear. The same pattern appears throughout the conquest narrative (Josh 2:9-11; 9:9-10) and in the NT mission: the gospel spreads because what Christ has done is witnessed and reported. Balak's fear is the fear of the nations before YHWH's power — Ps 2:1-3 frames this as the nations' futile raging against YHWH's anointed, and Balak's subsequent attempt to curse Israel is precisely this raging.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Moab was overcome with fear of the people, because they were many. Moab was in dread of the people of Israel. The fear produced by YHWH's victories is not an enemy's healthy respect but a terror that drives them to occult means. Christ's own presence produced similar fear: the Gerasene demoniac's community 'were afraid and... asked him to leave' (Luke 8:35-37). The power that should have drawn them to worship instead drove them to rejection — because what they feared was the power itself, not its source. Balak's fear is the type of every attempt to neutralize divine power by means other than submission to it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moab said to the elders of Midian: 'This horde will now lick up all that is around us, as the ox licks up the grass of the field.' The coalition between Moab and Midian against Israel anticipates the pattern of the nations' coalition against YHWH's anointed in Ps 2:2: 'The kings of the earth set themselves, and the rulers take counsel together, against the LORD and against his Anointed.' Christ's death was similarly the product of a coalition between Pilate (Rome) and the chief priests (Jerusalem), coordinating against the one they feared (Acts 4:27-28).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Balak sent messengers to Balaam: 'A people has come out of Egypt.' The 'out of Egypt' description identifies Israel by their originating redemptive act — the exodus. This becomes a Christological identification in Matt 2:15, which applies Hos 11:1 to Jesus: 'Out of Egypt I called my son.' The exodus that defined Israel's identity becomes the pattern for Christ's own flight to and return from Egypt. Balak names Israel by their exodus; Matthew names Christ by his. The pagan king's description of the people by their divine deliverance inadvertently points forward to the Son who recapitulates the people's story.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Come now, curse this people for me... I know that he whom you bless is blessed, and he whom you curse is cursed.' Balak's acknowledgment of Balaam's power over blessing and cursing frames the entire narrative as a contest between blessing and cursing — which is ultimately a Christological theme. Gal 3:13-14: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us... so that in Christ Jesus the blessing of Abraham might come to the Gentiles.' The curse-contest Balak initiates finds its resolution not in Balaam's oracles but in the cross, where the curse was absorbed once for all and blessing released for all nations.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The elders of Moab and Midian went with fees for divination in their hand. The payment for prophetic speech commodifies YHWH's word — treating the divine oracle as a purchasable service. This is precisely what Peter rebuked Simon Magus for (Acts 8:18-20: 'Your silver perish with you, because you thought you could obtain the gift of God with money'). Christ himself refused the economic logic of the temple market ('you have made it a den of robbers,' Matt 21:13) and commanded his disciples: 'You received without paying; give without pay' (Matt 10:8). The fees for divination stand as the type of every attempt to purchase what God gives freely.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Lodge here tonight, and I will bring back word to you, as YHWH speaks to me.' Balaam's willingness to consult YHWH is unexpected from a pagan diviner — it reflects YHWH's sovereign use of unlikely instruments to accomplish his purposes. The pattern of YHWH speaking through unexpected vessels appears throughout Scripture: Cyrus (Isa 45:1), the Magi (Matt 2:1-12), the centurion at the cross ('Truly this was the Son of God,' Matt 27:54). The unexpected prophets who speak truth about YHWH and his purposes point toward the one who is himself the unexpected revelation: a Galilean carpenter's son who is the eternal Son of God.</p>",
    "9": "<p>God came to Balaam and said, 'Who are these men with you?' The divine interrogation is not informational — YHWH knows who they are. It is the rhetorical opening of a moral examination: why are they here? What do they want? What do you want? Christ used the same interrogative approach: 'Who do you say that I am?' (Matt 16:15); 'What do you want me to do for you?' (Mark 10:51); 'What are you looking for?' (John 1:38). The divine questions are not requests for information but invitations to self-examination in the presence of the one who already knows the answer.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Balaam said to God: 'Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab, has sent to me.' The faithful report of the human request to the divine; Balaam brings the king's proposal to YHWH for evaluation. This is the prophetic model of intercession — bringing human situations to God for judgment. Christ's high-priestly intercession follows a different logic: he does not merely report to God what humans need but 'always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25), standing permanently before the Father on behalf of his people, not merely consulting YHWH about whether to comply with a human request.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Come, curse this people for me. Perhaps I shall be able to fight against them and drive them out.' Balak's stated purpose: military advantage through spiritual means. The attempt to weaponize prophetic/spiritual power for political-military ends is the persistent temptation the kingdoms of this world offer to those with spiritual gifts. Jesus resisted this explicitly: after the feeding of the five thousand, 'Jesus, knowing they intended to come and make him king by force, withdrew again to a mountain by himself' (John 6:15). The kingdom Christ announced is not secured by cursing enemies but by giving one's life for them.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'You shall not go with them. You shall not curse the people, for they are blessed.' YHWH's absolute prohibition — the blessing is irrevocable. This is the OT foundation for Paul's declaration: 'If God is for us, who can be against us?... Who shall separate us from the love of Christ?' (Rom 8:31, 35). The blessing pronounced on Abraham's descendants (Gen 12:3) is the covenant guarantee that stands behind YHWH's prohibition. Christ is the one in whom the blessing is ultimately secured: 'Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, who has blessed us in Christ with every spiritual blessing in the heavenly places' (Eph 1:3) — the blessing Balak tried to reverse is now permanently established in the Son.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Balaam rose in the morning and said to the princes of Balak: 'Go to your own land, for YHWH has refused to let me go with you.' The obedience to YHWH's clear prohibition; Balaam's initial compliance is real. The morning context is significant — the morning is the time of clear-headed decision, before the pressure of the day's temptations fully mount. Christ's own mornings were spent in prayer (Mark 1:35: 'rising very early in the morning, while it was still dark, he departed and went to a desolate place, and there he prayed') — the morning hours being the time of realignment with the Father's will before the day's ministry began.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The princes of Moab reported to Balak: 'Balaam refuses to come with us.' The first failure of the diplomatic mission; the word YHWH has given cannot be purchased or persuaded. The same pattern appears when the religious authorities sent people to arrest Jesus: 'The officers then came to the chief priests and Pharisees, who said to them, \"Why did you not bring him?\" The officers answered, \"No one ever spoke like this man!\"' (John 7:45-46). The mission to capture or silence YHWH's chosen instrument fails repeatedly because YHWH's word and work cannot be suppressed by human authority.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Balak sent again more princes, more honorable and more numerous. The escalation of status and honor as an argument for compliance; the implicit message is that Balaam's refusal was a category error about who was asking. The same status-argument was used against Jesus: 'Have any of the authorities or the Pharisees believed in him?' (John 7:48). The implication was that the crowd's belief in Jesus was worthless without the validation of the honorable. Christ consistently rejected the argument from status: 'What is highly esteemed among men is an abomination in the sight of God' (Luke 16:15).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Let nothing hinder you from coming to me, for I will surely do you great honor.' The offer of honor as the ultimate inducement to abandon faithfulness to YHWH's word. This is the form of the temptation Jesus faced in the wilderness: 'All these I will give you, if you will fall down and worship me' (Matt 4:9). The tempter offered not just wealth but glory and honor — precisely what Balak offers Balaam. Christ refused because he came to receive his glory from the Father, not from human or demonic sources: 'I do not receive glory from people' (John 5:41). The honor Balak offered was the world's honor — the shadow of the true glory Christ would receive at his resurrection and ascension.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I will surely do you great honor, and whatever you say to me I will do. Come, curse this people for me.' The offer of unlimited compliance — 'whatever you say' — as the price of one act of spiritual betrayal. The tempter's logic is always the same: unlimited benefit in exchange for one compromise. Christ faced this in its most direct form: 'All these I will give you' for one act of worship (Matt 4:9). Balaam's response — 'I could not go beyond the word of YHWH my God' (v.18) — is the prophetic version of Christ's response: 'You shall worship the Lord your God and him only shall you serve' (Matt 4:10). The constraint of the word of God is the only defense against unlimited temptation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Though Balak were to give me his house full of silver and gold, I could not go beyond the command of YHWH my God, to do either good or bad of my own accord.' Balaam's correct statement of prophetic constraint is the OT articulation of a principle Christ embodied completely: 'I do nothing on my own authority, but speak just as the Father taught me' (John 8:28); 'I have not spoken on my own authority, but the Father who sent me has himself given me a commandment — what to say and what to speak' (John 12:49). The prophet constrained by YHWH's word is the type of the Son who acts only in accordance with the Father's will — the difference being that Balaam's constraint was external while Christ's was intrinsic to his eternal relation to the Father.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Stay here tonight, that I may know what more YHWH will say to me.' Balaam seeks a second divine consultation despite having received a clear answer. The desire for a different answer than the one received is a subtle form of unbelief — hoping that another inquiry might produce a more accommodating response. Christ warned against this pattern: 'Do not keep asking God and treating him as if he had not answered, seeking a sign when the signs have been given' (cf. Matt 16:4: 'An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign'). YHWH's first answer was clear; the second consultation produces permission, not revision — a permission that comes with conditions Balaam will violate in his eagerness.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Rise, go with them; but only do what I tell you to do.' YHWH's permissive will accommodates Balaam's persistence while reiterating the constraint. The permission does not change the prohibition on cursing — it only allows the journey. God's accommodation of human persistence within sovereign constraints appears throughout Scripture (1 Sam 8:7-9 with Israel's demand for a king; Luke 11:8 with the persistent friend). Christ's pattern is the same in Gethsemane: 'not my will, but yours, be done' (Luke 22:42) — accepting what the Father wills, not demanding accommodation of a preferred alternative. Balaam's second petition and God's conditional permission is the type of prayer that receives what it asks for in a way that tests the integrity of the asker.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Balaam rose in the morning, saddled his donkey, and went with the princes of Moab. The narrator's note that Balaam rose and went — quickly, eagerly, in the morning — implies an enthusiasm for the journey that exceeded the caution YHWH's permission implied. The contrast with Moses's obedient but heavy-laden departure or with Christ's 'I set my face to go to Jerusalem' (Luke 9:51) is telling: Balaam went because there was something in the going he wanted, not simply because YHWH had permitted it. The eagerness itself is the warning sign. The journey that follows will be intercepted by the very God who permitted it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>God's anger was kindled because he went, and the angel of YHWH took his stand in the way as his adversary. The angel of YHWH acting as adversary (<em>satan</em>, lit. 'one who opposes') is a striking reversal: the divine messenger becomes the obstacle. Many interpreters identify the angel of YHWH throughout the Pentateuch as a Christophany — a pre-incarnate appearance of the Son. If so, the one who opposed Balaam's misguided eagerness on the road to Moab is the same one who was lifted up on a cross to absorb the consequences of humanity's misguided eagerness to pursue its own ways. The adversary on the road is the Savior at the cross.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The donkey saw the angel of YHWH standing in the road, with a drawn sword in his hand. The donkey's supernatural sight contrasts with Balaam's blindness. The creature sees what the prophet cannot. This inversion — the animal perceiving spiritual reality while the prophet is blind — is the most pointed judgment on Balaam's spiritual state. Christ's own words about spiritual blindness run in the same direction: 'You have hidden these things from the wise and understanding and revealed them to little children' (Matt 11:25). The donkey is the 'little child' of the Balaam narrative — the humble creature who sees what the prestigious diviner cannot.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The angel of YHWH stood in a narrow path between the vineyards, with a wall on either side. The spatial constriction is deliberate — the path narrows until there is no room to maneuver around the divine obstacle. Christ uses the same image: 'Enter by the narrow gate. For the gate is wide and the way is easy that leads to destruction, and those who enter by it are many. For the gate is narrow and the way is hard that leads to life' (Matt 7:13-14). The angel's position in the narrow path creates the conditions for confrontation — the same conditions the narrow way creates for every disciple. The narrow place is where the divine obstacle forces the decision that the wide road defers.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The donkey pressed against the wall, crushing Balaam's foot. The physical consequence of trying to evade the divine obstacle — the wall is the only other option, and it injures. When God places an obstacle in the path of his servant's misaligned purposes, the attempts to work around it produce damage. Peter's attempt to go his own way after Christ's prediction of his denial ended in the courtyard beside the fire (John 18:18) — the injury of self-assertion when Christ had warned against the path. Balaam's crushed foot is the type of every injury that comes from pressing through the divine obstacle rather than heeding it.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The angel moved again to a narrow place where there was no way to turn either to the right or to the left. The escalating constriction: first a wide road, then a narrow path, now a place with no way to turn. The progressive narrowing of options until the divine confrontation is unavoidable. Jacob's night at the Jabbok (Gen 32:24-30) followed the same pattern — pursued, cornered, unable to escape — until the confrontation became the blessing. Christ's passion narrative follows the same constriction: the crowds, the arrest, the trial, the cross — each step narrowing until the moment of ultimate confrontation and ultimate redemption.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The donkey lay down under Balaam, and Balaam's anger was kindled. The donkey's final act — lying down — is passive non-compliance with Balaam's direction. The anger that follows is the anger of frustrated entitlement: the tool that should serve my purposes has stopped serving them. Christ's confrontation of the same entitled anger appears in the parable of the prodigal son's elder brother (Luke 15:28-30) and the laborers in the vineyard (Matt 20:11) — those who were supposed to serve the master's purposes complain when the master's purposes diverge from their expectations. The lying-down donkey is the type of every instrument that refuses to cooperate with what God has not authorized.</p>",
    "28": "<p>YHWH opened the mouth of the donkey, and it said to Balaam: 'What have I done to you, that you have struck me these three times?' The miracle of the donkey's speech is YHWH's most direct rebuke of Balaam: a dumb animal is given prophetic speech to confront the prophet who would not listen to God's angel. 2 Pet 2:16 cites this as the rebuke of a prophet's madness: 'a speechless donkey spoke with human voice and restrained the prophet's madness.' Christ himself performed the same kind of reversal when he silenced his opponents with the testimony of those they despised: 'if these were silent, the very stones would cry out' (Luke 19:40). The opened mouth of the donkey is the extreme case of YHWH's ability to give speech to any creature to accomplish his purpose.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'You have made a fool of me. I wish I had a sword in my hand, for then I would kill you.' Balaam's rage at the instrument of his rebuke is the response of pride confronted by humiliation. The desire to destroy the messenger of divine correction — whether it is a donkey, a prophet, or the Son of God — is the fundamental response of unrepentant pride: silence the corrective voice. Christ's parable of the tenants makes this explicit (Matt 21:38-39): 'This is the heir. Come, let us kill him and have his inheritance.' The vineyard tenants' response to the son is Balaam's response to the donkey — kill the obstacle rather than heed it.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Have I ever been accustomed to do this to you? From all your life until now, have I done this to you?' The donkey's reasoned appeal to Balaam's own experience: the animal's past behavior as evidence against the current accusation. The argument from character and history is a valid form of testimony. Christ made the same appeal: 'Which of you convicts me of sin? If I tell the truth, why do you not believe me?' (John 8:46). The appeal to track record — to the consistent behavior that stands against the accusation — is the defense of the one whose life itself is the testimony. Balaam could not deny the donkey's point; the Pharisees could not deny Christ's works.</p>",
    "31": "<p>YHWH opened the eyes of Balaam, and he saw the angel of YHWH standing in the way, with his drawn sword in his hand. The opening of Balaam's eyes is the climactic spiritual gift of the entire encounter — more significant than the donkey's speech. Spiritual sight is what all the prophetic equipment had failed to give him. Christ's healings of physical blindness throughout the Gospels (John 9; Mark 10:51-52; Matt 9:27-30) are the antitype of every divine eye-opening: 'one thing I do know, that though I was blind, now I see' (John 9:25). The opening of Balaam's eyes to see the angel mirrors what Christ does for every spiritually blind person who encounters him.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Why have you struck your donkey these three times? Behold, I have come out as an adversary, because your way is perverse before me.' The angel's rebuke names Balaam's error precisely: his way is 'perverse' (<em>yarat</em>) — headstrong, reckless. The three strikes map onto the three spatial constrictions. What YHWH tried to communicate through progressive spatial narrowing, Balaam answered with progressive violence against the innocent instrument. The progressive escalation of spiritual conflict before the final confrontation is the Gethsemane pattern reversed: where Christ progressively submitted in prayer ('not my will'), Balaam progressively resisted through force.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'The donkey turned aside before me these three times. If she had not turned aside from me, surely just now I would have killed you and let her live.' The donkey's obedience preserved Balaam's life — the humble creature protected the man who was beating it. This inverted the expected order: the servant protected the master from the consequences of the master's own perversity. Christ absorbed the consequences of his people's perversity — 'he was pierced for our transgressions' (Isa 53:5); 'the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all' (Isa 53:6). The donkey that bore Balaam's misdirected anger and preserved him is a creaturely shadow of the one who bore human sin and preserved sinners.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'I have sinned, for I did not know that you were standing in the road against me. Now therefore, if it is evil in your sight, I will go back.' Balaam's confession is honest but incomplete — he confesses ignorance rather than wrong desire. The conditional offer to turn back ('if it is evil in your sight') lacks the unconditional repentance that the situation demands. Christ's confrontation of half-repentance in the Gospels follows the same discernment: the rich young ruler's correct moral record combined with an unwillingness to give up the one thing (Mark 10:21-22). Balaam's 'I have sinned' without full relinquishment of the underlying desire is the type of the confession that acknowledges consequence without transforming the will.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Go with the men, but only speak the word that I shall tell you.' The restatement of the constraint with the permission reaffirmed. Balaam will go, but his speech will be entirely controlled. Jesus's own claim about his speech operates on the same principle from within: 'I have not spoken on my own authority, but the Father who sent me has himself given me a commandment — what to say and what to speak. And I know that his commandment is eternal life. What I say, therefore, I say as the Father has told me' (John 12:49-50). The difference between Balaam and Christ is that Balaam's constraint was external (YHWH overrode his desire) while Christ's was intrinsic (the Son never desired to speak other than what the Father gave him).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Balak went out to meet Balaam at the boundary of Moab at the edge of the Arnon. The king's personal reception of the prophet demonstrates the honor Balak attaches to Balaam's presence. The contrast with Christ's reception is deliberate: those who came to Christ expecting a different kind of king (military, conquering) were disappointed; those who received him as he was received eternal life. Balak received Balaam as a weapon to be deployed; the proper reception of YHWH's sent one is worship, not weaponization. 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11) — the non-reception is the NT counterpart of Balak's instrumental reception.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'Did I not send urgently for you? Why did you not come to me? Am I not able to honor you?' Balak's complaint assumes that his offer of honor should have been sufficient motivation for immediate compliance. The assumption that earthly honor is an adequate motivation for prophetic faithfulness misunderstands the nature of prophetic vocation. Christ confronted the same confusion when people followed him for the wrong reasons (John 6:26: 'you are seeking me not because you saw signs but because you ate your fill of the loaves'). The one who comes with a true commission does not come for the honor of the one who sent the invitation; he comes because of the one who gave the commission.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Have I now any power of myself to speak anything? The word that God puts in my mouth, that must I speak.' This is Balaam's most important self-description — and it is exactly what Christ claimed for himself: 'I do not speak on my own authority, but the Father who sent me has himself given me a commandment — what to say and what to speak' (John 12:49). The constraint Balaam describes as external compulsion, Christ described as the expression of his unity with the Father. The prophetic model — speaking only what YHWH gives — reaches its fullest expression in the one who is himself the Word of God, not merely the vessel for it (John 1:1,14).</p>",
    "39": "<p>Balaam went with Balak, and they came to Kiriath-huzoth. The movement toward the scene of the oracles; the journey that will produce the unexpected blessings. The road to Kiriath-huzoth is the road to the place where YHWH will override all human plans with his sovereign word. Similarly, the road to Calvary — which appeared to be the road to silence and defeat — became the road to the greatest speech ever spoken over humanity: the Father's vindication of the Son through resurrection, declaring him 'the Son of God in power' (Rom 1:4).</p>",
    "40": "<p>Balak sacrificed oxen and sheep and sent portions to Balaam and to the princes who were with him. The pagan sacrificial hospitality — sharing the feast with the prophet — creates the social bond of host and guest before the spiritual work begins. The meal as covenant relationship runs throughout the biblical narrative: the Passover, the fellowship offerings, the Last Supper. But Balak's shared meal is a manipulation, not a covenant — the hospitality is in service of obtaining a curse. Christ's shared meals were the opposite: they expressed genuine fellowship and cost him social standing ('a friend of tax collectors and sinners,' Matt 11:19) without extracting anything from the guests.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Balak took Balaam to Bamoth-baal, and from there he could see a portion of the people of Israel. The vantage point at the high places of Baal — seeing Israel from a distance and from the perspective of an opposing god. The attempt to curse from a distance, without entering into the life of the people. Christ's incarnation took the opposite approach: he came near, not distant; he dwelt among his people (John 1:14), ate with them, touched the untouchables, and saw their condition from within rather than from a height. The distant view from Bamoth-baal is the opposite of the incarnational approach — YHWH's answer to human need is not a curse pronounced from a height but a Son sent into the depths.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>'Build me seven altars here and prepare seven bulls and seven rams for me.' The elaborate ritual preparation — fourteen animals across seven altars — is the pagan system's maximum effort to compel divine speech. The number seven signals completeness and cosmic significance. But all the ritual apparatus cannot force YHWH's hand; what comes will come entirely on YHWH's terms. Christ's approach to prayer and sacrifice was the opposite of manipulation: 'Not as I will, but as you will' (Matt 26:39) was the stance of one who had already offered himself completely to the Father's will, needing no ritual mechanism to get YHWH's attention because he was always in the Father's presence (John 1:18).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Balak did as Balaam had said, and Balak and Balaam offered a bull and a ram on each altar. The meticulous compliance with Balaam's ritual instructions reveals Balak's desperation — he will do whatever the prophet requires. The fourteen sacrificed animals represent the maximum effort of the pagan sacrificial system. Hebrews directly contrasts this repetitive multiplication of sacrifice with Christ's one offering: 'when Christ had offered for all time a single sacrifice for sins, he sat down at the right hand of God' (Heb 10:12). The seven-altars, fourteen-animals system of Numbers 23 is one data point in the OT pattern that Hebrews argues required the single, final, sufficient sacrifice.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Stand beside your burnt offering and I will go. Perhaps YHWH will come to meet me, and whatever he shows me I will tell you.' The 'perhaps YHWH will come' is the uncertainty inherent in all pagan divination — and even in Balaam's YHWH-consulting. The contrast with Christ's certainty of access to the Father is categorical: 'I know that you always hear me' (John 11:42); 'All things that the Father has are mine' (John 16:15); 'I am always with you' (John 16:32). The 'perhaps' of prophetic consultation gives way to the certainty of the Son's relationship with the Father — not a hoping that YHWH will come but the permanent communion of the Son who has never left the Father's presence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>God met Balaam, and Balaam said to him: 'I have arranged the seven altars and I have offered on each altar a bull and a ram.' The human reporting of human effort as grounds for divine response: here is what I have done; now what will you do? This is the logic of merit and transaction that the entire sacrificial system was misread as supporting. Christ reversed the direction entirely: the Father acts first, the Son responds in obedience; the Son acts first, believers respond in faith. 'We love because he first loved us' (1 John 4:19). The transactional logic of Balaam's report to God is the type of every attempt to obligate YHWH by human performance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH put a word in Balaam's mouth and said: 'Return to Balak and thus you shall speak.' The divine word placed in the human mouth — the moment of prophetic inspiration. Moses described the same process: 'YHWH said to me, \"I will put my words in his mouth\"' (Deut 18:18). All of this prophetic word-placing points toward the Word who became flesh: Christ is not a vessel for the divine word but the Word himself (John 1:1,14). The prophet receives words placed in his mouth; the Son IS the Word, such that his speaking is not the receiving of a deposit but the expression of eternal divine speech in human form.</p>",
    "6": "<p>He returned to Balak, who was standing beside his burnt offering with all the princes of Moab. The audience waiting for the curse oracle: the king, his princes, the sacrificial smoke still rising. The whole apparatus of pagan power assembled to receive what it had purchased. Christ's oracles were delivered differently — not to kings and their courts assembled in ritual expectation, but 'the common people heard him gladly' (Mark 12:37); to fishermen mending nets, to a Samaritan woman at a well, to a tax collector in a tree. The contrast between Balak's royal reception of Balaam and the ordinary contexts of Christ's teaching is the contrast between power-seeking and kingdom-announcing.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'From Aram Balak has brought me, the king of Moab from the eastern mountains: Come, curse Jacob for me, and come, denounce Israel!' The first oracle begins by naming the commission that will be refused: the purpose behind the summoning was curse and denunciation. The same reversal pattern governs the cross: those who crucified Christ intended his silence and condemnation but received the proclamation of forgiveness ('Father, forgive them,' Luke 23:34) and the declaration of the kingdom ('Today you will be with me in paradise,' Luke 23:43). The intent to curse produced blessing; the intent to silence produced the loudest word ever spoken.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'How can I curse whom God has not cursed? How can I denounce whom YHWH has not denounced?' The rhetorical questions establish the impossibility of the commission: the divine blessing cannot be reversed by human or prophetic effort. Paul's answer to the same question in Romans 8: 'If God is for us, who can be against us?... Who shall bring any charge against God's elect? It is God who justifies. Who is to condemn? Christ Jesus is the one who died — more than that, who was raised — who is at the right hand of God, who indeed is interceding for us' (Rom 8:31-34). The impossibility of cursing what YHWH has blessed is grounded, in the new covenant, in Christ's death, resurrection, and intercession.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'For from the top of the crags I see him, from the hills I gaze at him; behold, a people dwelling alone, and not counting itself among the nations!' Israel's unique covenant status — distinct from all other nations — is the content of Balaam's first oracle. The church inherits this distinctiveness in Christ: 'you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession, that you may proclaim the excellencies of him who called you out of darkness into his marvelous light' (1 Pet 2:9). The 'dwelling alone' is not isolation but distinctiveness — a people defined by their relationship to YHWH rather than by the categories of the surrounding world.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Who can count the dust of Jacob or number the fourth part of Israel? Let me die the death of the upright and let my end be like his!' Balaam involuntarily utters the Abrahamic promise (Gen 13:16) and expresses a longing for the righteous death. The death of the upright that Balaam longed for is the death that Christ died — not the death of a sinner under judgment but the death of the perfectly righteous one, which he died voluntarily for others. The longing to 'die the death of the upright' is the OT expression of the NT hope: 'For to me to live is Christ, and to die is gain' (Phil 1:21). The death Balaam desired is the death Christ provided — and his death makes it available to all who are in him.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Balak said to Balaam: 'What have you done to me? I brought you to curse my enemies, and behold, you have blessed them.' The king's indignation at the reversal: blessing where curse was expected. This is the constant pattern of those who encounter YHWH's word expecting one thing and receiving another. The crowds who watched Jesus die expecting defeat saw resurrection. The disciples on the Emmaus road expecting the end of their hope ('we had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel,' Luke 24:21) were encountered by the risen Christ who opened the Scriptures and their hearts. The reversal of curse into blessing — Balaam's first oracle — is the shadow of the resurrection reversal that is the gospel's center.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Balaam answered: 'Must I not take care to speak what YHWH puts in my mouth?' The faithful prophet's answer to the pressure of the king's disappointment: the word comes from above, not from human negotiation. The pressure to soften, modify, or reverse YHWH's word under the pressure of powerful human displeasure is the persistent temptation of every prophetic figure. Christ faced it directly: 'If you are the Son of God, come down from the cross' (Matt 27:40) — the demand that he modify the divine commission under the pressure of human expectation. His refusal to come down was his faithfulness to the Father's word, just as Balaam's refusal to curse was his faithfulness to YHWH's constraint.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Balak said: 'Come with me to another place from which you may see them. You shall see only a fraction of them and shall not see them all. Then curse them for me from there.' The attempt to change the oracle by changing the vantage point — perhaps seeing only part of Israel will produce a different result. This is the logic of selective attention: if you can't curse the whole, perhaps you can curse a part. Jesus confronted the same logic in the question about paying taxes to Caesar (Matt 22:17-21) — attempts to get a partial answer that could be used against him by limiting the question's frame. Truth seen from any angle is still truth; changing the vantage point does not change what YHWH has determined.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Balak took Balaam to the field of Zophim, on the top of Pisgah, and built seven altars and offered a bull and a ram on each altar. The second location, the second round of sacrifice — the same method attempted again. The definition of futility: repeating the same action expecting a different result. But the repetition of the ritual makes the comparison to Hebrews' argument even more explicit: 'if those first covenants had been faultless, there would have been no occasion to look for a second' (Heb 8:7). The repeated attempt at Pisgah is the OT picture of the inadequacy of any system that must be repeated — and the contrast with Christ's one sufficient sacrifice.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Stand here beside your burnt offering while I meet YHWH over there.' The separation of the prophet from the king during the oracle — the prophetic consultation requires distance from the human authority. Christ's pattern of withdrawing for prayer (Mark 1:35; Luke 5:16; 6:12) reflects the same need for unmediated access to the Father without human pressure. The difference is that Christ withdrew to pray without human authority as the interested party — his prayer was alignment with the Father's will, not consultation about how to deal with a demanding king.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH met Balaam and put a word in his mouth and said: 'Return to Balak, and thus shall you speak.' The second oracle is given exactly as the first — YHWH meets, YHWH puts, Balaam delivers. The consistency of the pattern despite the change of location demonstrates that the oracle is not a function of geography or ritual but of YHWH's sovereign determination. 'Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away' (Matt 24:35) — the word spoken on Bamoth-baal is the same word spoken on Pisgah is the same word that will be spoken in every context until the end: blessing for Israel that cannot be reversed.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Balaam came to Balak, who was standing beside his burnt offering with the princes of Moab. Balak said to him: 'What has YHWH spoken?' The king's direct question anticipates the oracle — he has learned that what Balaam says is what YHWH says, not what Balak wants. The capacity to hear YHWH's actual word rather than the word one wants to hear is a prerequisite of faith. Christ's disciples often wanted to hear confirmation of their own expectations: 'Lord, are you at this time going to restore the kingdom to Israel?' (Acts 1:6). The answer they received redirected them entirely. The question 'What has YHWH spoken?' is the right question; the difficulty is receiving the answer faithfully.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Rise, Balak, and hear; give ear to me, O son of Zippor.' The command to rise and hear before the oracle — the posture of attentive reception. Christ's repeated call 'He who has ears to hear, let him hear' (Matt 11:15; 13:9,43) is the NT form of the same summons. The prophetic oracle demands full attention from the one who is about to receive it — because what follows will not be what was expected, and only careful hearing can receive unexpected truth without immediately rejecting it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'God is not man, that he should lie, or a son of man, that he should change his mind. Has he said, and will he not do it? Or has he spoken, and will he not fulfill it?' The divine immutability and faithfulness as the ground of the oracle's reliability. This becomes the foundation of Hebrews' argument about the oath-bound promise: 'it is impossible for God to lie' (Heb 6:18). The incarnation appears to complicate this verse — God becomes 'a son of man' in Christ — but the incarnation does not introduce lying or mind-changing into the Godhead; it expresses the eternal faithfulness of God in human form. The eternal Word who cannot lie takes on human speech; the one who cannot change his mind expresses the unchanging divine purpose in human obedience.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'Behold, I received a command to bless: he has blessed, and I cannot revoke it.' The irrevocability of the divine blessing is the content of the second oracle. 'The gifts and the calling of God are irrevocable' (Rom 11:29). Christ's own declaration: 'No one will snatch them out of my hand. My Father, who has given them to me, is greater than all, and no one is able to snatch them out of the Father's hand' (John 10:28-29). The blessing that cannot be revoked — given to Abraham, confirmed to Israel, and now declared by a pagan prophet constrained by YHWH — is the covenant faithfulness that reaches its fullest expression in Christ's permanent high-priestly advocacy for his people.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'He has not beheld misfortune in Jacob, nor has he seen trouble in Israel. YHWH their God is with them, and the shout of a king is among them.' The covenant-presence formula: YHWH with his people, and a king among them. This is the Immanuel oracle in nascent form. Isaiah's elaboration (Isa 7:14: 'God with us'; 9:6-7: 'a child is born, a son is given... and the government shall be upon his shoulder') receives its ultimate fulfillment in Matthew's formula citation: 'They shall call his name Immanuel (which means, God with us)' (Matt 1:23). The shout of a king among Israel — implicit in the wilderness camp with YHWH at its center — becomes explicit in the Gospel proclamation: the King of kings has arrived.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'God brings them out of Egypt and has as it were the horns of the wild ox.' The exodus confession by a pagan prophet: the foundational redemptive act acknowledged even by those outside the covenant. Matthew 2:15 applies the 'out of Egypt' language to Christ directly via Hosea 11:1: 'Out of Egypt I called my son.' The Matthean application is not a proof-text but a typological fulfillment: the Son of God recapitulates Israel's story, going down to Egypt and being called out, so that what Israel was as a type (YHWH's son in Hos 11:1) Christ is as the antitype. The pagan prophet's exodus confession in Numbers 23 anticipates the evangelist's Christological application in Matthew 2.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'For there is no enchantment against Jacob, no divination against Israel; now it shall be said of Jacob and Israel, \"What has God done!\"' The futility of all occult power against the covenant people; the exclamation about YHWH's works. The final line — 'What has God done!' — is the proper response to every divine act. At the resurrection, the disciples' response was exactly this: 'The Lord has risen indeed!' (Luke 24:34); 'My Lord and my God!' (John 20:28). The exclamatory response to YHWH's acts that Balaam's oracle anticipates becomes the Christological confession that defines the church: what God has done in Christ is the content of the gospel and the reason for all Christian doxology.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Behold, a people! As a lioness it rises up and as a lion it lifts itself; it does not lie down until it has devoured the prey and drunk the blood of the slain.' The lion imagery for Israel finds its ultimate focus in the tribe of Judah (Gen 49:9-10) and the Messiah: 'Weep no more; behold, the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has conquered' (Rev 5:5). The lion that 'does not lie down until it has devoured the prey' is the image of total conquest — which Christ accomplishes not through physical force but through the cross: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, by triumphing over them in him' (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Balak said to Balaam: 'Do not curse them at all, and do not bless them at all.' The retreat to a neutral position — neither curse nor bless. But YHWH's word cannot be contained within a neutrality; it is always either blessing or cursing, never merely descriptive. 'Whoever is not with me is against me' (Matt 12:30). The demand for neutrality about YHWH's word is itself a refusal of blessing. The subsequent attempt to find a third location for a third oracle (vv.27-28) reveals that Balak has not truly accepted neutrality — he still hopes for a curse. The retreat to neutrality is a tactical maneuver, not a genuine acceptance of YHWH's sovereign word.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Balaam answered Balak: 'Did I not tell you, \"All that YHWH says, that I will do\"?' The reiteration of the fundamental constraint, now in its third occurrence. The repetition in the narrative — Balaam says the same thing in the same way three times — establishes that this is not variable but fixed. Three is the number of confirmation in the OT legal system (Deut 17:6; 19:15). The triple confirmation of Balaam's constraint is the narrative's way of saying: this is established truth. Christ's own promises carry the same triple confirmation structure in John 14-16 (repeated 'truly, truly I say to you') — establishing beyond doubt what the Father has committed to do.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Balak said to Balaam: 'Come now, I will take you to another place. Perhaps it will please God that you may curse them for me from there.' The third attempt, the third location — Peor. The persistence is driven by desperation, not faith. But the Peor that Balak chose as the site of hoped-for cursing became the site of Israel's worst apostasy in ch25 (the Baal of Peor incident). The place names in the Balaam narrative carry shadows: Peor will be remembered not for a successful curse but for Israel's catastrophic defection. Christ predicted his own disciples' Peor-moment: 'All of you will fall away because of me this night' (Matt 26:31) — the place of anticipated victory became the place of failure, before the resurrection reversed everything.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Balak took Balaam to the top of Peor, which overlooks the desert. Three locations, three vantage points, three sets of seven altars — and YHWH's word will be the same from every angle. The repetition of the ritual scaffolding serves the narrative argument: no amount of preparation, no change of location, no increase of sacrifice can alter what YHWH has determined to say. The sovereignty of the divine word over all human arrangements is absolute. Christ's own death — the ultimate human arrangement against YHWH's purpose — became the supreme demonstration of YHWH's sovereign control: 'This Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed' (Acts 2:23).</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Build me here seven altars and prepare me here seven bulls and seven rams.' The third round of sacrifice, by now clearly mechanical — the ritual stripped of any expectation of efficacy and done only because there is no other option. When ritual becomes mechanical repetition without faith, it is the religious form of desperation. Hebrews' argument about the OT sacrificial system (Heb 10:1-4) makes precisely this point: 'the same sacrifices that are continually offered every year cannot make perfect those who draw near. Otherwise, would they not have ceased to be offered?' The third preparation at Peor is the narrative enactment of the inadequacy of repeated sacrifice — the setup for the fourth oracle that will transcend all the ritual and speak of the coming Star.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Balak did as Balaam said and offered a bull and a ram on each altar. The final round of human preparation complete; what follows is entirely YHWH's initiative. The Spirit comes on Balaam (24:2) without any ritual summons — the Spirit moves where it wills (John 3:8), and the most important oracle of the entire cycle is given not through divination but through the Spirit's sovereign coming. Pentecost follows the same logic: the disciples prepared (gathered, waited, prayed) but the Spirit came with wind and fire at the Father's sovereign initiative (Acts 2:1-4). The preparation is not causal; the Spirit's coming is entirely YHWH's gracious gift.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>When Balaam saw that it pleased YHWH to bless Israel, he did not go, as at other times, to look for omens, but set his face toward the wilderness. The pivotal shift: Balaam abandons his divination apparatus and simply looks at Israel. The surrender of the oracle-seeking method in favor of open receptivity to whatever YHWH will give. Christ's own posture was this receptivity from within: 'I seek not my own will but the will of him who sent me' (John 5:30). The prophet who stops manipulating and simply looks — and receives the Spirit — is the shadow of the Son who always looks to the Father without ever seeking to determine the outcome in advance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Balaam lifted his eyes and saw Israel camping tribe by tribe, and the Spirit of God came upon him. The sight of the ordered covenant community — Israel arranged according to YHWH's design — is the visual stimulus for the Spirit's coming. The community itself, as YHWH has arranged it, is a vehicle of revelation. Paul's letter to the Ephesians moves in the same direction: the church as the body of Christ is itself the revelation of YHWH's wisdom: 'through the church the manifold wisdom of God might now be made known to the rulers and authorities in the heavenly places' (Eph 3:10). The ordered community of YHWH's people is not merely the recipient of revelation but its vehicle.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The oracle of Balaam the son of Beor, the oracle of the man whose eye is opened.' The third oracle's opening describes Balaam as one with an opened eye — the eye-opening of ch22 (when YHWH opened his eyes to see the angel) is now the defining characteristic of his prophetic identity. The opened eye is the prerequisite for the vision that follows. Christ's gift to his disciples was the opening of eyes and understanding: 'Then he opened their minds to understand the Scriptures' (Luke 24:45); 'I pray... that the eyes of your hearts might be enlightened' (Eph 1:17-18). The opened eye of Balaam is the type of the Spirit-given sight that every disciple needs to see the kingdom.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'The oracle of one who hears the words of God, who sees the vision of the Almighty, falling down with his eyes uncovered.' The prostration before the Almighty while maintaining opened eyes is the paradox of prophetic vision: overwhelmed by YHWH's majesty, and yet given sight to see. This is the posture of every genuine encounter with divine glory in Scripture: Ezekiel fell on his face (Ezek 1:28); Isaiah was undone (Isa 6:5); John fell as though dead (Rev 1:17). Christ's response in each case is the same as the angel's response to Balaam: the fallen one is raised: 'Fear not' (Rev 1:17). The vision that overwhelms is followed by the commission that sends.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'How lovely are your tents, O Jacob, your encampments, O Israel!' The exclamation of beauty over the ordered covenant camp. Beauty as a theological category — the community arranged according to YHWH's design is beautiful. Christ's vision of his gathered people is similarly characterized by desire and beauty: 'I do not ask for these only, but also for those who will believe in me through their word, that they may all be one, even as you, Father, are in me, and I in you' (John 17:20-21). The unity of the community is both its beauty and its testimony. The beautiful tents of Jacob point to the beautiful gathered community of the new covenant.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Like palm groves that stretch afar, like gardens beside a river, like aloes that YHWH has planted, like cedar trees beside the waters.' The beauty of YHWH's intentional planting — the covenant people as YHWH's garden. This imagery runs throughout Scripture: the Garden of Eden, the vineyard of Israel (Isa 5:1-7), the vine planted by YHWH (Ps 80:8-11), and Christ's own 'I am the true vine, and my Father is the vinedresser' (John 15:1). The covenant community is YHWH's planting — and the gardener who tends it, protects it, and prunes it is ultimately revealed to be the Son who is himself the vine in whom the branches must abide.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Water shall flow from his buckets, and his offspring shall be in many waters; his king shall be higher than Agag, and his kingdom shall be exalted.' The water of blessing flowing from the patriarch's household; the king exalted above all other kings. Christ is the source of living water: 'Whoever believes in me, as the Scripture has said, Out of his heart will flow rivers of living water' (John 7:38). And his kingdom is exalted above every earthly dominion: 'at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father' (Phil 2:10-11). The buckets of water and the exalted king of Balaam's oracle find their fulfillment in the one who gives living water and reigns over all.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'God brings him out of Egypt; he has as it were the horns of the wild ox; he shall eat up the nations, his adversaries, and shall break their bones in pieces and pierce them through with his arrows.' Matthew 2:15 applies the 'out of Egypt' language to Christ via Hosea 11:1, making the exodus pattern Christological. The 'horns of the wild ox' represent irresistible divine power in the service of redemption. The conquest language that follows — eating nations, breaking bones — is the judgment imagery that Christ fulfills not through military force but through the gospel: 'I came to cast fire on the earth' (Luke 12:49); 'Now is the judgment of this world; now will the ruler of this world be cast out' (John 12:31).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He crouched, he lay down like a lion and like a lioness; who will rouse him up? Blessed are those who bless you, and cursed are those who curse you.' The lion of Judah at rest — unconquerable because voluntary, not because forced (Gen 49:9-10). John's vision in Revelation completes the image: the Lion who has conquered is also the Lamb who was slain (Rev 5:5-6). The one who lies down like a lion does so not in defeat but in the rest of accomplished redemption. And the blessing-cursing formula of the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 12:3) reappears here in Balaam's oracle — because the covenant promise made to Abraham finds its fulfillment in the one from whom all blessings flow and against whom all cursing shatters.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Balak struck his hands together in anger and said to Balaam: 'I called you to curse my enemies, and behold, you have blessed them these three times.' The three blessings where three curses were sought; the fury of frustrated human expectation. Peter's three denials were followed by Christ's three restoration questions (John 21:15-17) — the triple failure transformed into triple affirmation. The three blessings Balaam pronounced despite Balak's triple attempt to produce curses follows the same numerical pattern of reversal: where human persistence tried to produce condemnation, YHWH's sovereign word produced blessing, three times confirmed.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Flee to your own place. I said I would honor you greatly, but YHWH has held you back from honor.' The world's verdict on faithfulness to YHWH: you missed the honor. Herod made the same offer to those who would serve his purposes (Matt 14:7: 'whatever you ask I will give you'), and it produced the head of John the Baptist. Christ's disciples faced the same calculus: 'Blessed are you when others revile you and persecute you and utter all kinds of evil against you falsely on my account. Rejoice and be glad, for your reward is great in heaven' (Matt 5:11-12). The honor Balak offered and YHWH held back was the world's honor; what YHWH gave instead was a place in the prophetic record pointing to the coming Messiah.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Balaam said to Balak: 'Did I not say to your messengers whom you sent to me: \"Though Balak were to give me his house full of silver and gold, I could not go beyond the word of YHWH, to do either good or bad of my own accord\"?' The triple reiteration of the prophetic constraint comes to its resolution: Balaam delivered what was given, nothing more and nothing less. Christ's summary of his own mission follows the same structure: 'I have glorified you on earth, having accomplished the work that you gave me to do' (John 17:4). The prophetic constraint — speaking only what YHWH gives — is the external form of the Son's intrinsic alignment with the Father's will: 'I always do the things that are pleasing to him' (John 8:29).</p>",
    "13": "<p>'What YHWH says, that will I speak.' The summary formula: the reduction of the prophetic office to its essence. The prophet is the one through whom YHWH speaks; the prophet's own will, preferences, and interests are entirely subordinated to the divine word. Christ's claim is the fullest expression of this principle: 'My teaching is not mine, but his who sent me' (John 7:16); 'The words that I say to you I do not speak on my own authority, but the Father who dwells in me does his works' (John 14:10). The difference between the prophet's 'what YHWH says, I speak' and the Son's 'the words I speak are the Father's' is the difference between channel and source, between vessel and Word.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'And now, behold, I am going to my people. Come, I will let you know what this people will do to your people in the latter days.' The final oracle is specifically eschatological — 'in the latter days' (<em>be'acharit hayamim</em>). This temporal marker signals that what follows is not merely historical prediction but Messianic prophecy. The 'latter days' in OT prophecy consistently point to the age of the Messiah (Isa 2:2; Jer 23:20; Dan 10:14; Mic 4:1). The shift from historical oracles about Israel's blessing to eschatological prophecy about 'the latter days' elevates the fourth oracle to a different register — the register in which the star, the scepter, and the ultimate ruler will be revealed.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'The oracle of Balaam the son of Beor, the oracle of the man whose eye is opened.' The fourth oracle begins with the same opening as the third — the opened-eye formula reappears, signaling that what follows requires the same level of spiritual sight as the third oracle but now directed toward the eschatological horizon. The eyes opened in the encounter with the angel (ch22), the opened eyes of the third oracle, and the opened eyes required for the Messianic fourth oracle form a progression: from seeing the present obstacle (the angel), to seeing the present community (Israel), to seeing the coming one (the Star). The opened eye is always YHWH's gift, never a human achievement.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'The oracle of one who hears the words of God and knows the knowledge of the Most High, who sees the vision of the Almighty, falling down with his eyes uncovered.' The fourth oracle's opening expands the third oracle's description to include 'the knowledge of the Most High' — the eschatological oracle requires a higher grade of revelation. Christ claimed this knowledge in its fullest form: 'No one knows the Son except the Father, and no one knows the Father except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him' (Matt 11:27). The prophet who knows 'the knowledge of the Most High' is the shadow of the Son who is himself the knowledge of the Father — who does not merely possess divine knowledge but is the revelation of it.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'I see him, but not now; I behold him, but not near: a star shall come out of Jacob, and a scepter shall rise out of Israel; it shall crush the forehead of Moab and break down all the sons of Sheth.' The messianic heart of the Balaam oracles. The star from Jacob was recognized as messianic in Second Temple Judaism (Dead Sea Scrolls, 1QM 11:6-7; CD 7:18-20) and provided the cognomen for Bar Kokhba in the revolt of 132-135 CE. Christ claimed and received this identification: 'I am the root and the descendant of David, the bright morning star' (Rev 22:16). The Magi came following a star (Matt 2:2) — the celestial phenomenon pointing to the one who is himself the Star of Jacob. The star Balaam saw 'not yet and not near' arrived at Bethlehem and will appear in his fullness at the consummation (Rev 22:16).</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Edom shall be dispossessed; Seir also, his enemies, shall be dispossessed. Israel is doing valiantly.' The conquest of Edom — the perennial antagonist of Israel — is part of the Messianic king's victory. Isaiah's vision of the divine warrior coming from Edom with garments red with blood (Isa 63:1-6) is the OT's most graphic depiction of this conquest. Revelation's vision of the rider on the white horse (Rev 19:11-16) is the fulfillment: 'He will tread the winepress of the fury of the wrath of God the Almighty' (Rev 19:15). The total conquest of every opposing power — represented by Edom and Seir — is accomplished by the Star of Jacob who is also the King of kings.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'And one from Jacob shall exercise dominion and destroy the survivors of cities.' The singular ruler — 'one from Jacob' — exercises total dominion. The singular is Messianic: not Israel collectively but one person from Jacob who will rule. Ps 2:8-9 develops the same figure: 'Ask of me, and I will make the nations your heritage, and the ends of the earth your possession.' Rev 11:15 announces the fulfillment: 'The kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ, and he shall reign forever and ever.' The 'one from Jacob' who exercises dominion in Balaam's oracle is the one whom Daniel saw receiving dominion 'from the Ancient of Days' (Dan 7:13-14) and whom John saw as the Lamb who alone is worthy to open the scroll (Rev 5:5-9).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Then he looked at Amalek and took up his discourse: 'Amalek was the first among the nations, but its end is utter destruction.' The oracle against Amalek — Israel's first military opponent (Exod 17:8-16) — pronounces its eventual destruction. The eschatological destruction of every power that opposed YHWH's people is the Messianic king's final work: 'Then comes the end, when he delivers the kingdom to God the Father after destroying every rule and every authority and power. For he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet. The last enemy to be destroyed is death' (1 Cor 15:24-26). Amalek was the first enemy; death is the last. The Messianic king defeats both.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Then he looked at the Kenites and took up his discourse: 'Enduring is your dwelling place, and your nest is set in the rock.' The rock as the symbol of security; the Kenites' stability grounded in natural defensibility. But the next verse pronounces their end as well. Only one rock provides ultimate security: 'The rain fell, and the floods came, and the winds blew and beat on that house, but it did not fall, because it had been founded on the rock' (Matt 7:25). Christ is the rock: 'I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it' (Matt 16:18); 'that Rock was Christ' (1 Cor 10:4). The Kenites' nest set in the rock is the type of the security that only the messianic Rock provides.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Nevertheless, Kain shall be burned when Asshur takes you away captive.' Even the seemingly secure nest in the rock will face destruction. No earthly fortress is ultimate. The oracle against Kain (the Kenites) follows the pattern of all the national oracles: security that seems permanent is temporary; only YHWH's eternal purposes stand. 'Where is the one who is wise? Where is the scribe? Where is the debater of this age? Has not God made foolish the wisdom of the world?' (1 Cor 1:20). The nations and their securities pass; what endures is the word of YHWH and the kingdom of his Christ.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Alas, who shall live when God does this?' The eschatological question of the oracle — the terror of the divine judgment that sweeps all the nations. The question anticipates the NT's 'Who can stand?' (Rev 6:17) before the day of YHWH's wrath. Christ's answer to the eschatological question: 'I am the resurrection and the life. Whoever believes in me, though he die, yet shall he live, and everyone who lives and believes in me shall never die' (John 11:25-26). The question 'who shall live?' is answered by the one who is himself the Life — who passed through judgment and came out the other side with resurrection life to give to all who trust in him.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'But ships shall come from Kittim and shall afflict Asshur and Eber; and he too shall come to utter destruction.' The oracle extends to the most distant nations — ships from the western sea (Kittim = Cyprus/the west) advancing to judgment. The eschatological horizon is universal: all the nations, in their successive waves of power, come under YHWH's judgment. Christ's universal reign encompasses every human empire: 'All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18). The successive empires of Balaam's oracle (Amalek, Kain/Kenites, Asshur, the western ships) are the OT's panoramic view of what Christ's universal authority already encompasses and what will be made fully visible at the consummation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Balaam rose and went back to his place, and Balak also went his way. The departure is the narrative's quiet conclusion: the oracles are spoken, the parties return to their places, the drama ends without the curse ever being uttered. Balaam's subsequent apostasy (he counseled Balak to send Midianite women to seduce Israel into idolatry, Num 31:16; Rev 2:14) means that the Balaam narrative's end is not the end of his story. The one who spoke the most glorious messianic oracle in the wilderness books became a warning (2 Pet 2:15; Jude 11). The word of God comes through imperfect vessels who may not embody it; the Star of Jacob spoken of by Balaam is not made less real by Balaam's subsequent failure — the prophetic word transcends the prophet who bore it.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('christ', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(existing, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('christ', 'numbers', existing)
    total = sum(len(existing.get(ch, {})) for ch in ['22','23','24'])
    print(f'ch 22-24: {total} verses in output')
    print('Numbers 22-24 christ commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
